Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Ghana Oil Co., Union Bank of Nigeria

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-06-24T16:00:09Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-24/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-ghana-oil-co-union-bank-of-nigeria.html
Kenya’s All-Share Index slid for a
third day, falling 0.4 percent to 69.81 by the 3 p.m. close in
Nairobi, the lowest close since April 2010.  The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index advanced for a
third day, adding 0.3 percent to 25,271.61 by the 2:30 p.m.
close in Lagos, according an e-mailed statement from the
exchange. The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index fell for a
third day, retreating 0.6 percent to 1,178.99 by the 3 p.m.
close in Accra.  Namibia ’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  jumped 1.4
percent to 812.75, snapping two days of declines by the 4 p.m.
close in Windhoek. Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index climbed 0.1 percent
to 2,088.16 by the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis .  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Ghana Oil Co. (GOIL GN), the second-biggest operator of
gasoline stations in the West African nation, gained 1 pesewa,
or 3.2 percent, to 32 pesewas, the highest since June 6. The
company plans to buy back as much as 15 percent of its issued
shares this year, Chairman William Asomaning said at a
 shareholders’ meeting  yesterday.  Union Bank of Nigeria Plc (UBN NL), a lender bailed out by
the nation’s central bank in 2009, advanced 11 kobo, or 4.8
percent, to 2.42 naira, taking its total gain to 12 percent this
week, the most since March. Chief Executive Officer Funke
Osibodu said the bank plans to conclude recapitalization in
September after reaching a deal with investors.  To contact the reporter on this story:
